In this study we map SNPs to pathways from the KEGG pathways database, a curated collection of functional gene pathways representing current knowledge of molecular interaction and reaction networks ( http://www.genome.jp/kegg/pathway.html ).

Pathways databases such as those provided by KEGG ( http://www.genome.jp/kegg/pathway.html ), Re- actome ( http://www.reactome.org/ ) and Biocarta ( http://www.biocarta.com/ ) typically clas- sify pathways across a number of functional domains, for example apoptosis, cell adhesion or lipid metabolism; or crystallise current knowledge on specic disease-related molecular reaction net- works.

For pathway mapping, we used the KEGG canonical pathway gene sets obtained from from the Molecular Signatures Database v3.0 ( http://www.broadinstitute.org/gsea/msigdb/index.jsp ), which contains 186 gene sets, which map to a total of 5,267 distinct genes, with many genes mapping to more than one pathway.
